WEBVTT

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:03.120
<v Speaker 1>What was the word for what?

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:10.480
<v Speaker 1>What when it's not a question is loke

00:00:10.719 --> 00:00:16.800
<v Speaker 1>Lok for example if you want to say I saw what you're doing.

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:18.320
<v Speaker 1>This is not a question

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:19.240
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:20.920
<v Speaker 1>I saw what you're doing.

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:23.240
<v Speaker 1>Here the what is not a question.

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:25.320
<v Speaker 1>Here it's lo que.

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:27.640
<v Speaker 1>I cooked what they're eating.

00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:28.920
<v Speaker 1>I cooked.

00:00:28.619 --> 00:00:30.539
<v Speaker 1>what they're eating.

00:00:30.539 --> 00:00:33.180
<v Speaker 1>Here, what is not a question?

00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:33.739
<v Speaker 1>No.

00:00:33.739 --> 00:00:37.980
<v Speaker 1>Yo cosine, I cooked lo que comen.

00:00:37.980 --> 00:00:41.340
<v Speaker 1>Or lo que están comiendo, if we mean right now.

00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:41.980
<v Speaker 1>So what

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:52.320
<v Speaker 1>Not as a question is lo que how would you say I don't want you to speak about what we spoke about but you know we don't need this about

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:57.840
<v Speaker 1>So the first bit is I don't want you to speak and let's speak informally.

00:00:57.840 --> 00:00:59.600
<v Speaker 1>I don't want you to speak.

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:01.600
<v Speaker 1>I don't want that you speak

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:05.280
<v Speaker 2>No quiero que hables.

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:05.840
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:12.880
<v Speaker 1>No quiero que hables about is it de you could use or you could use

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:15.520
<v Speaker 1>Sobre.

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:16.240
<v Speaker 1>Sobre.

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:17.200
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:22.159
<v Speaker 1>So no quiero que hables de or sobre what we spoke about.

00:01:22.159 --> 00:01:24.880
<v Speaker 1>And we can just say what we spoke.

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:27.479
<v Speaker 2>Lo que hablamos.

00:01:27.479 --> 00:01:29.159
<v Speaker 1>Yes, it's the same in the past.

00:01:29.159 --> 00:01:30.680
<v Speaker 1>So give it to me now altogether.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:33.560
<v Speaker 1>I don't want you to speak about what we spoke about.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:36.360
<v Speaker 1>From the beginning and thinking it through again.

00:01:37.159 --> 00:01:42.840
<v Speaker 2>No quiero que hables sobre lo que hablamos.

00:01:43.399 --> 00:01:48.679
<v Speaker 1>No quiero que hables sobre lo que hablamos, o no quiero que hables de lo que hablamos.

00:01:49.439 --> 00:01:51.920
<v Speaker 1>But that sentence could be ambiguous, no?

00:01:51.920 --> 00:02:01.360
<v Speaker 1>I mean in your mind when you're creating this sentence you will have the context very strongly in your mind that you're thinking about what we spoke about the other day

00:02:01.340 --> 00:02:06.060
<v Speaker 1>But that doesn't necessarily mean that the person receiving it has that same context in their mind.

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:08.459
<v Speaker 1>They might, depends what your conversation is about.

00:02:08.459 --> 00:02:10.220
<v Speaker 1>But if you don't have a context

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:12.480
<v Speaker 1>that's shared, it could be ambiguous.

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:17.280
<v Speaker 1>You could understand, I don't want you to speak about what we speak about generally.

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:20.720
<v Speaker 1>Because of course we have hablamos, which can be past or present.

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:24.960
<v Speaker 1>No quiero que hables sobre lo que hablamos generally.

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:28.080
<v Speaker 1>So there's two ways here that you could uh clarify.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:31.520
<v Speaker 1>You could add something like the other day, el otro día.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.280
<v Speaker 1>No quiero que hables sobre lo que hablamos el otro día.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:46.160
<v Speaker 1>So you are showing with some time expression that it was past, or you could use the line in the past, what we were speaking about, because here it's interchangeable.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:49.560
<v Speaker 1>The meaning changes so slightly and both meanings are fine.

00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:49.880
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:54.280
<v Speaker 1>If we look at English, I don't want you to speak about what we were speaking about.

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:58.200
<v Speaker 1>I don't want you to speak about what we spoke about.

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:04.560
<v Speaker 1>So maybe here in Spanish you choose the line in the past just so it's obvious that you're talking about the past.

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:05.840
<v Speaker 1>So let's give it another go.

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:07.440
<v Speaker 1>Using the line in the past

00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:12.780
<v Speaker 1>I don't want you to speak about what we were speaking about.

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:15.660
<v Speaker 1>I don't want you to speak informally still

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:22.580
<v Speaker 2>No quiero que hables sobre lo que hablábamos.

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:23.300
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:27.220
<v Speaker 1>No quiero que hables sobre lo que hablábamos.

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:36.120
<v Speaker 1>Necessity, necessity in Spanish is, do you know remember what to do with it words to make them Spanish?

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:38.480
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:42.800
<v Speaker 1>So necesity becomes necesidad.

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:44.240
<v Speaker 1>Necesidad.

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:47.760
<v Speaker 1>To need is necesitar.

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:48.960
<v Speaker 2>Necesitar.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:50.640
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:53.340
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I need?

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:54.380
<v Speaker 2>Necesito.

00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:55.420
<v Speaker 1>Necesito.

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:57.420
<v Speaker 1>I need you to prepare it.

00:03:57.420 --> 00:03:58.860
<v Speaker 1>Let's speak formally.

00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:01.980
<v Speaker 1>I need you to prepare it formally

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:07.040
<v Speaker 2>In English again it would be I need that you prepare it.

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:08.079
<v Speaker 1>Exactly.

00:04:08.079 --> 00:04:11.360
<v Speaker 2>Necessito che lo repare.

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:12.480
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:15.340
<v Speaker 1>Necesito que lo prepare.

00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:17.100
<v Speaker 1>This is to you formally.

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:23.259
<v Speaker 1>If you wanted to make it clear that you were speaking to you or not speaking about him or her, how would you do that here?

00:04:23.259 --> 00:04:25.020
<v Speaker 1>I need you to prepare it

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:30.140
<v Speaker 2>Necesito que usted lo prepare.

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:31.020
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:04:31.020 --> 00:04:33.740
<v Speaker 1>Necessito que usted lo prepare.

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:36.940
<v Speaker 1>Necesito que lo prepare usted.

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:38.300
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:42.880
<v Speaker 1>So with quiero que necesito que we're seeing two things that they have in common.

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:46.400
<v Speaker 1>We have a verb like quiero, necesito.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:52.960
<v Speaker 1>a verb that's showing what we want to occur in the world, expressing our subjectivity, let's say, in this way.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:59.040
<v Speaker 1>And we have the structural similarity that the mood tense is coming after ke

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.960
<v Speaker 1>To be short of, to be short of, to be missing, to lack is faldar.

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:10.960
<v Speaker 1>Quite uncomfortable translations, but this is a very common verb in Spanish.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:11.960
<v Speaker 1>Faltar.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:15.160
<v Speaker 1>It's used very often, this verb in Spanish.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:19.880
<v Speaker 1>For example, you could say, I need you to prepare what's missing.

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:24.940
<v Speaker 1>I need you to prepare what's missing, what's left over, what we need to do still.

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:28.380
<v Speaker 1>So again, formally, I need you to prepare

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:32.300
<v Speaker 2>Necessito que repare.

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:32.860
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:35.820
<v Speaker 1>What's missing?

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.220
<v Speaker 2>Lo que falta.

00:05:37.820 --> 00:05:44.220
<v Speaker 1>Necessito che prepare lo que falta and lo que because the what here is not a question.

00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:45.260
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:47.980
<v Speaker 1>The noun is also used quite often.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:50.300
<v Speaker 1>The noun is falta, la falta

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:52.820
<v Speaker 1>So falta means lack.

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:53.780
<v Speaker 1>Lack.

00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:57.620
<v Speaker 1>So if I say falta de consideración, what does it mean?

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:00.100
<v Speaker 1>Falta de consideración.

00:06:01.259 --> 00:06:03.580
<v Speaker 2>All right, lack of consideration.

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:05.740
<v Speaker 1>Good, lack of consideration.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:11.180
<v Speaker 1>It's also used with respect, falta de respecto, lack of respect.

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:14.620
<v Speaker 1>And it's also used in the expression asefalta.

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:16.540
<v Speaker 1>It makes lack.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:22.140
<v Speaker 1>It makes lack, which just is another way of saying it's necessary, but it's very common.

00:06:22.140 --> 00:06:24.060
<v Speaker 1>And asefalta ke

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.960
<v Speaker 1>Of course, is followed by this mood tense.

00:06:27.960 --> 00:06:35.800
<v Speaker 1>In the same way that we do with quiero que, necesito ke, we will follow it with this mood tense.

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:38.840
<v Speaker 1>So if you wanted to say using asefalta

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:42.640
<v Speaker 1>It is necessary that we eat soon.

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:44.480
<v Speaker 1>What was the word for soon?

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:45.920
<v Speaker 1>Is it pronto?

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:48.240
<v Speaker 1>That's that's it.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:51.120
<v Speaker 1>In Italian actually it means ready pronto

00:06:51.180 --> 00:07:01.740
<v Speaker 1>This is why when Italians answer the phone they say Bronto because historically let's say there was a operator there connecting the wires and they were there going, Ready?

00:07:01.740 --> 00:07:02.220
<v Speaker 1>Are you ready?

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:02.860
<v Speaker 1>Is it ready?

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:04.140
<v Speaker 1>Can you hear me?

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:12.900
<v Speaker 1>But uh s in Spanish it's uh soon, like the British slang, people say in England, queer soon.

00:07:12.900 --> 00:07:18.660
<v Speaker 1>So it makes lack ace falta, uh it makes lack that we eat soon.

00:07:19.680 --> 00:07:23.440
<v Speaker 2>Sorry, couldn't you explain again how why does that make sense?

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:25.919
<v Speaker 2>It makes lack that we eat soon.

00:07:25.919 --> 00:07:26.960
<v Speaker 1>It makes lack

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:31.860
<v Speaker 1>would be the literal translation but literal translations are often uncomfortable.

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:35.060
<v Speaker 1>No especially when we're talking about fixed expressions

00:07:34.879 --> 00:07:41.039
<v Speaker 1>So asefalda is an extremely common expression, quite difficult to translate comfortably.

00:07:41.039 --> 00:07:44.000
<v Speaker 1>Just another way of saying it's necessary.

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:48.400
<v Speaker 1>So it makes la co a cefalta that we eat soon?

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:49.680
<v Speaker 1>How would it be?

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:52.080
<v Speaker 2>Acefalta che

00:07:55.199 --> 00:07:58.240
<v Speaker 1>Hace falta que comamos pronto.

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:06.879
<v Speaker 1>So hace falta you will hear around a lot, and falta is a noun, you will hear it in especially in phrases like falta de respetto and lack of respect.

00:08:06.879 --> 00:08:09.120
<v Speaker 1>You hear that a lot.

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:16.060
<v Speaker 1>And faltar as a verb to lack or to be missing is also very useful.

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:21.020
<v Speaker 1>To prefer in Spanish is preferir, preferir.

00:08:21.020 --> 00:08:21.900
<v Speaker 2>Preferir.

00:08:21.900 --> 00:08:22.700
<v Speaker 1>Preferir.

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:24.460
<v Speaker 1>How is I prefer?

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:26.220
<v Speaker 2>Prefero.

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:27.420
<v Speaker 1>It should be.

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:28.460
<v Speaker 2>Prefiero.

00:08:28.460 --> 00:08:29.100
<v Speaker 1>Better.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:30.220
<v Speaker 1>Prefiero.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:31.420
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:37.980
<v Speaker 1>So again, if you say I prefer him to stay, we're not going to say I prefer him to stay.

00:08:37.980 --> 00:08:40.460
